# Format-preserving multi-block .http writeback. Editing a request from a
# multi-block source and Ctrl+S should rewrite *just* that block — not
# clobber the file with a single curl line.

# Seed a 3-block .http file. The blocks are separated by `### name`. Cursor
# starts at the very top, so we'll move it into block "two" before sending.
write requests.http "### one\nGET https://example.com/one\n\n### two\nPOST https://example.com/two\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{\"a\": 1}\n\n### three\nGET https://example.com/three\n"

open requests.http

# Drop the cursor into block "two" (line 4 is `### two` in the file, 0-based).
# Five Down arrows lands on the body line of block two, comfortably inside it.
key down
key down
key down
key down
key down

# Fire the request — opens a Request pane. The send itself will fail (no
# network) but `send_request_from_active` runs synchronously up to the spawn,
# capturing `source_block_name = Some("two")` on the new pane.
command http.send

# Tab into Edit mode so we can mutate the URL.
key tab

# Append " EDIT" to the URL field (focus starts at Url, cursor at end).
type " EDIT"

# Save. Multi-block path: splices block "two" with the edited request,
# leaves blocks "one" and "three" alone.
command file.save

# The other two blocks survived verbatim.
expect file requests.http contains "### one\nGET https://example.com/one"
expect file requests.http contains "### three\nGET https://example.com/three"

# Block "two" got edited in place.
expect file requests.http contains "POST https://example.com/two EDIT"

# We did NOT collapse the file to a single curl line.
expect file requests.http lacks "curl '"
